For a primate with a digestive system similar to that of humans, it is difficult to meet their own amino acid needs with the plant resources available in the savanna.
In addition, the failure to the to carry out such activities has serious consequences: slowdown in growth, malnutrition and, ultimately, death.
The most easily accessible plant resources would have been the proteins found in leaves and legumes, but for primates like us they are difficult to digest, unless they are cooked.
Animal foods (such as ants, thermites, eggs) are not only easy to digest, but they provide a high amount of protein, containing all the essential amino acids.
In light of all this, it should come as no surprise that our very ancestors solved their own “protein problem” in a way that savanna chimpanzees do today.
Sleep disruption is the process of intentional awakening that occurs during the normal sleep period, followed by sleep recovery (10–60 minutes later).
