The Sundarbans are the largest coastal mangrove belt in the world and stretch 80 km (50 mi) from the coast in the hinterland of Bangladesh and India.
The Sundarbans have been declared a UNESCO World Heritage by UNESCO. The part of the forest by the Indian territory is named Sundarbans National Park.
However, forests are not only made up of mangrove swamps; they also contain what remains of the imposing jungles that once covered the Ganges.
The Sundarbans cover an area of 3,850 km², of which about one-third is made up of swampy areas.
Since 1966, the Sundarbans have become a sanctuary for wildlife; the area is estimated to have 400 royal tigers of Bengal and about 30,000 maculate deer.
